# compiler/home_tu.kai — the single source of truth for the decl-to-TU
# partition. `home_tu` answers which physical translation unit a decl
# emits its code into, shared by every backend modular codegen (the C
# `emit_program_modular` and the native KIR partitioner).
#
# The result is the PHYSICAL emission unit, aligned to the mangled
# symbol: a root-file `pub fn f` mangles to `kai_<file>__f` and lives in
# `<file>.c`, so its home is `Some(<file>)` even though it was authored
# in the root. It is NOT the logical module identity of a decl. A
# consumer asking whether two decls share a logical module (protocol-op
# shadowing) must canonicalise `Some(target_mod)` against `None` on its
# own; reusing `home_tu` there would reintroduce the per-module shadow
# bug.
#
# Only DFn and DType carry a home here. By the time codegen runs, every
# decl kind that emits a symbol has already been LOWERED to a DFn (DImpl
# methods, DAxiom FFI shims, DConst readers, DEffect default clauses),
# so the surviving DConst / DEffect / wrapper nodes emit no per-TU body.
# Mapping them to their module would spawn an empty TU and shift the
# partition, so they ride root like every other bodyless decl.

import compiler.ast

#[doc("The translation unit a decl emits into: `None` for the root TU, `Some(m)` for module `m`. The single source of the codegen partition, shared across backends.")]
pub fn home_tu(d: Decl) : Option[String] = match d {
  DFn(_, _, _, _, _, _, _, _, _, mo) -> mo
  DType(_, _, _, _, _, _, mo)        -> mo
  _                                  -> None
}
